    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1938-07-23T02:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1938-07-23T02:00:00-05:00" n="46"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d46">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">600.939/227: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The First Secretary of Embassy in China</hi> (<persName
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Salisbury</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Peiping</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1938-07-23T15:00:00+08:00"
                            >July 23, 1938—3 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received July 23—11 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>464. Embassy’s 456, July 20, 1 p.m.,<note n="52" xml:id="d46fn52">Not
                        printed.</note> and Tientsin’s 137, July 22, 3 p.m. A secretary of the
                    Japanese Embassy called this morning and stated informally that embargo will be
                    lifted from most materials not urgently needed by the military, including
                    lambskin plates, lambear plates, lambhead plates, and lambleg plates and all
                    kinds of goat and kid skins but that the embargo continues for the time being on
                    tanned and untanned lambskins. He stated that this means the embargo is lifted
                    on almost all kinds of materials heretofore exported to the United States. He
                    expects detailed and official information will be available in 2 or 3 days.</p>
                <p>Repeated to Embassies Hankow, Tokyo and Consulate Tientsin.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Salisbury</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
